    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>Which is better, MBTI or DISC?</summary>
        <p>Neither is objectively better — they measure different things. The MBTI measures cognitive preferences (how you process information and make decisions), while the DISC measures behavioral tendencies (how you act in work and social situations). The MBTI is better for broad self-understanding and career exploration, while the <a href="/test/disc-personality-test/">DISC</a> is better for improving workplace communication and leadership effectiveness. Many people benefit from taking both.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is the Enneagram more accurate than MBTI?</summary>
        <p>The Enneagram and MBTI measure fundamentally different things, so comparing accuracy is like comparing a thermometer to a barometer. The MBTI describes how you think and process information, while the Enneagram reveals why you do what you do by identifying your core motivation and fear. Many people find the Enneagram feels more deeply accurate because it addresses the emotional and motivational layer that the MBTI does not reach. However, neither has the empirical validation of the Big Five model.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can you be different types in MBTI and Enneagram?</summary>
        <p>Yes. Because the MBTI and Enneagram measure different aspects of personality, there is no direct correspondence between them. An INTJ could be an Enneagram 1, 3, 5, or 8. Two people who share the same MBTI type can have completely different Enneagram types, and vice versa. This is why taking both provides richer insight — they reveal different layers of your personality.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Which personality test should I take first?</summary>
        <p>If you are new to personality frameworks, the <a href="/test/personality-type-test/">MBTI</a> is a good starting point because it provides a broad, accessible overview. If you are focused on workplace performance, start with the DISC. If you are drawn to personal growth, start with the <a href="/test/enneagram-test/">Enneagram</a>. Ideally, take all three and compare the insights each provides.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Do companies prefer DISC or MBTI?</summary>
        <p>Both are widely used in corporate settings but for different purposes. The DISC is more commonly used for team communication training, sales coaching, and leadership development because its focus on observable behavior makes it easy to apply. The MBTI is more commonly used for career counseling, organizational development, and understanding cognitive diversity. Some organizations use both.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

